# Univocity Cursor Rules

## Solidity imports

**Always use explicit named imports.** Do not use wild/namespace imports.

- **Do:** `import {LibCose, TypeName} from "@univocity/cose/lib/LibCose.sol";`
- **Do:** `import {IUnivocity} from "@univocity/checkpoints/interfaces/IUnivocity.sol";`
- **Do not:** `import "@univocity/cose/lib/LibCose.sol";`
- **Do not:** `import "forge-std/Script.sol";` (without naming what you use)

Import only the types, libraries, interfaces, constants, or functions you need by name (e.g. `{P256}`, `{WitnetBuffer}`, `{LibCbor}`, `{peaks}`). This keeps dependencies visible and avoids pulling in unused symbols.

Apply this in:
- `src/**/*.sol`
- `script/**/*.sol`
- `test/**/*.sol`

## Comment wrapping (Solidity)

**All comments in Solidity source files** (including NatSpec, block comments, and
line comments) must follow these line-length rules:

- **Soft wrap at 79 characters.** Prefer breaking at punctuation boundaries
  (e.g. after a comma, period, or colon) so that lines stay at or under 79
  characters where possible.
- **Hard wrap at 100 characters.** No comment line may exceed 100 characters.
  If a line would exceed 100 characters, put the first word that extends beyond
  the limit on the next line (i.e. break so that the overflow word starts the
  new line). **Never split a word** (e.g. mid-identifier or mid-token) to meet
  the character limit; move the whole word to the next line.
- **URLs are exempt** from the 79/100 limit only when the URL starts on or
  before column 40 on that line. Exempt URLs may extend past 100 characters.
  If a URL would start after column 40, break the line so the URL starts on or
  before column 40 on the next line, then the URL may run long.
- **Tag continuation indent:** When wrapping comments for `@param`, `@return`,
  `@notice`, or `@dev`, continuation lines must be indented by 4 spaces
  relative to the line that introduces the tag. So the second and subsequent
  wrapped lines for that tag start 4 characters to the right of the content
  on the first line.
- **Second pass — re-join short lines:** After applying the 79-character soft
  wrap, do a final pass over the file. Where consecutive lines (comments or
  code) were split but the result is shorter than the 79-character target,
  re-join them into a single line so long as the joined line stays at or
  under 79 characters. Prefer fuller lines over unnecessarily broken ones.
- **Very long names are exempt.** Identifiers (function names, variable names,
  etc.) must not be split to satisfy the line limit. If the only way to stay
  under 79 characters would be to break in the middle of a name, leave the
  line as-is and allow it to exceed the limit for that line only.
- **Run forge fmt last.** After all manual formatting (wrapping, second pass,
  and any edits) is settled, run `forge fmt`. Do not manually re-wrap or
  “fix” formatting after running forge fmt; the canonical format is whatever
  forge fmt produces with `line_length = 79` in `foundry.toml`. Use
  `forge fmt --check` in CI to ensure the tree stays formatted.

Apply in: `src/**/*.sol`, `script/**/*.sol`, `test/**/*.sol`.
